alfe (bricscad backend) leaks file-destined output onto stdout

Status: closed (resolved on branch
claude/alfe-bricscad-stdout-fix-fv9q1r, alfe 1.2.7).

## Report

A user AutoLISP script that opens a file and writes to it with the
printing primitives -- e.g.

    (setq f (open "report.txt" "w"))
    (princ "hello" f)
    (print '(1 2 3) f)
    (close f)

saw "hello" and "(1 2 3)" show up on alfe's stdout (the drained
`protocol/stdout.txt` channel) instead of inside `report.txt`, which
was left empty. In other words: output destined for a file the script
opened kept coming out on stdout.

## Root cause

alfe shadows `print` / `princ` / `prin1` on the CAD side so that
interactive output is captured into the file-IPC stdout slot rather
than vanishing into the CAD's session log. There are two shadow
variants:

  1. The 1-arg shadows in
     `autolisp-front-end/source/runtime/autolisp-bootstrap.lsp`
     (the fallback for hosts whose `defun` lacks `&rest`).
  2. The variadic `(&rest args)` shadows emitted into
     `run-common.lsp` by
     `autolisp-front-end/source/file-protocol.lisp` when the host
     supports `&rest` -- the path BricsCAD V26 actually takes.

Both variants only ever consumed the *first* argument and dropped
AutoLISP's optional file-descriptor argument. The variadic version
even documented the drop as intentional:

    ;; (princ obj filedes)-> filedes silently dropped (alfe protocol
    ;;                       captures everything to protocol/stdout.txt;
    ;;                       routing per-call to an arbitrary handle is
    ;;                       out of scope for the bridge).

BricsCAD AutoLISP does not error on extra arguments to a user `defun`,
so `(princ obj f)` silently fell through to the stdout-capture branch
instead of writing to `f`.

The default in-process clautolisp backend was never affected -- its
Common-Lisp `princ`/`print`/`prin1` builtins
(`clautolisp/autolisp-builtins-core/source/api.lisp`) already honour
the optional file argument via `output-stream-for-file`.

## Resolution

Both shadow variants now honour the file-descriptor argument:

  - when a descriptor is supplied, the rendered text is written to
    that open file and the input object is returned;
  - when it is absent (the common no-descriptor call), the previous
    protocol-capture behaviour is preserved verbatim.

`autolisp-bootstrap.lsp` gains a small helper
`autolisp-write-string-to-file` that writes a string to an open
descriptor one character at a time via the (un-shadowed) `write-char`
-- this reaches the genuine file without needing the original,
now-shadowed, printer. The variadic shadows in `file-protocol.lisp`
reuse that helper (the bootstrap is always loaded before the bridge).

`print`-to-file reproduces AutoLISP's documented framing (a leading
newline before the value and a trailing space after it); `princ` uses
the princ-style rendering, `prin1` the read-able one -- matching the
clautolisp builtins.

The helper and its callers stay ASCII-only, per the standing rule for
the vendored runtime + bootstrap (any byte > 127 has historically
tripped a BricsCAD / clautolisp LOAD failure).

## Tests

`protocol-emit-run-common-lsp-installs-variadic-shadows` in
`autolisp-front-end/tests/file-protocol-tests.lisp` now asserts the
emitted `run-common.lsp` routes through `autolisp-write-string-to-file`
on the `(cadr args)` file-descriptor branch, and that the old
"filedes silently dropped" comment is gone so the drop cannot be
reinstated unnoticed. The existing
`vendored-runtime-lsp-paren-balance` test continues to pin paren
balance on the edited bootstrap.
